com.github.dm.jrt.stream

Class AbstractStreamChannel<IN,OUT>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.github.dm.jrt.stream.AbstractStreamChannel<IN,OUT>
  • Type Parameters:
    IN - the input data type.
    OUT - the output data type.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    ConfigurableBuilder<StreamChannel<IN,OUT>>, Channel, Channel.OutputChannel<OUT>, InvocationConfiguration.Configurable<StreamChannel<IN,OUT>>, StreamChannel<IN,OUT>, Iterable<OUT>, Iterator<OUT>

    public abstract class AbstractStreamChannel<IN,OUT>
extends Object
implements StreamChannel<IN,OUT>, InvocationConfiguration.Configurable<StreamChannel<IN,OUT>>
    Abstract implementation of a stream output channel.

    This class provides a default implementation of all the stream channel features. The inheriting class just needs to create routine and channel instances when required.

    Created by davide-maestroni on 01/12/2016.

      • backoffOn

        @NotNull
public StreamChannel<IN,OUT> backoffOn(@Nullable
                                                Runner runner,
                                                int limit,
                                                @NotNull
                                                Backoff backoff)
        Description copied from interface: StreamChannel
        Short for invocationConfiguration().withRunner(runner).withInputLimit(maxInputs) .withInputBackoff(backoff).apply().
        This method is useful to easily apply a configuration which will slow down the thread feeding the next routine concatenated to the stream, when the number of buffered inputs exceeds the specified limit. Since waiting on the same runner thread is not allowed, it is advisable to employ a runner instance different from the feeding one, so to avoid deadlock exceptions.
        Specified by:
        backoffOn in interface StreamChannel<IN,OUT>
        Parameters:
        runner - the configured runner.
        limit - the maximum number of buffered inputs before starting to slow down the feeding thread.
        backoff - the backoff policy to apply to the feeding thread.
        Returns:
        the configured stream.

      • collect

        @NotNull
public StreamChannel<IN,OUT> collect(@NotNull
                                              BiConsumer<? super OUT,? super OUT> consumer)
        Description copied from interface: StreamChannel
        Concatenates a stream accumulating data through the specified consumer.
        The output will be computed as follows: 
             

         consumer.accept(acc, input);
        where the initial accumulated value will be the the first input.
        The accumulated value will be passed as result only when the outputs complete.

        Note that the created routine will be initialized with the current configuration.
        Note also that this stream will be bound as a result of the call.

        Specified by:
        collect in interface StreamChannel<IN,OUT>
        Parameters:
        consumer - the bi-consumer instance.
        Returns:
        the concatenated stream instance.

      • retry

        @NotNull
public StreamChannel<IN,OUT> retry(@NotNull
                                            BiFunction<? super Integer,? super RoutineException,? extends Long> function)
        Description copied from interface: StreamChannel
        Returns a new stream retrying the whole flow of data until the specified function does not return null.
        For each retry the function is called passing the retry count (starting from 1) and the error which caused the failure. If the function returns a non-null value, that will represent the number of milliseconds to wait before a further retry. While, in case the function returns null, the flow of data will be aborted with the passed error as reason.

        Note that no retry will be attempted in case of an explicit abortion, that is, if the error is an instance of AbortException.

      • runSequentially

        @NotNull
public StreamChannel<IN,OUT> runSequentially()
        Description copied from interface: StreamChannel
        Sets the stream runner so that each input is sequentially passed through the whole chain.

        On the contrary of the default synchronous runner, the set one will make so that each routine in the chain will be passed any input as soon as it is produced by the previous one. Such behavior will decrease memory demands at the expenses of a deeper stack of calls. In fact, the default synchronous runner breaks up routine calls so to perform them in a sequential loop. The main drawback of this approach is that all input data are accumulated before actually being processed by the routine invocation.

        Note that the runner will be employed with asynchronous and parallel invocation modes, while the synchronous and serial modes will behave as before.

        Specified by:
        runSequentially in interface StreamChannel<IN,OUT>
        Returns:
        this stream.
        See Also:
        StreamChannel.async(), StreamChannel.parallel()
